      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Optical character recognition in production environments often stumbles on accuracy trade-offs, integration complexity, and unpredictable latency. Nanonets OCR S ocr is engineered to mitigate these issues through a transformer-based architecture optimized for diverse document types, from invoices to handwritten notes. This model delivers consistent performance via a REST API, making it suitable for high-throughput pipelines where reliability is non-negotiable."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In this post, we'll dissect the model's capabilities, walk through a full integration cycle, and provide concrete benchmarks based on real-world deployments. You'll gain actionable insights into configuring the API for your use case, handling edge cases, and comparing alternatives to make informed decisions. By the end, you'll have a clear path to deploying Nanonets OCR S ocr in your stack."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "h2",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Core Capabilities and Model Architecture"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Nanonets OCR S ocr supports a range of document processing tasks beyond basic text extraction. Key features include multi-language recognition (covering over 50 languages), table structure detection, and handwriting analysis with a reported accuracy of 98.5% on standard benchmarks. The model uses a vision transformer backbone, fine-tuned on proprietary datasets, which allows it to handle variations in lighting, orientation, and document quality without pre-processing."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For production teams, the API abstracts away model complexity, exposing endpoints for synchronous and asynchronous processing. This means you can submit images or PDFs and receive structured JSON responses with bounding boxes, confidence scores, and extracted text. The architecture is designed for horizontal scaling, ensuring that latency remains stable under load—a critical factor for services processing thousands of documents daily."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "ul",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "li",
            "children": [
              {
                "type": "lic",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Multi-format support",
                    "bold": true
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": Accepts JPEG, PNG, PDF, and TIFF inputs up to 20MB per file."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "li",
            "children": [
              {
                "type": "lic",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Structured output",
                    "bold": true
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": Returns text in paragraphs, lines, or words with spatial coordinates."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "li",
            "children": [
              {
                "type": "lic",
                "children": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Custom model training",
                    "bold": true
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": ": Available via Nanonets' platform for domain-specific adaptations, though this post focuses on the base OCR S model."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
