            "type": "text",
            "text": "Handling Multi-Page Documents"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For PDFs or multi-page TIFFs, the API processes each page separately and returns an array of predictions. You can specify page ranges using the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "pages",
            "code": true
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " parameter to optimize costs. Always check the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "processing_time",
            "code": true
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " field to monitor latency—values above 2 seconds may indicate a need for image optimization or API tier upgrade."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "h2",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Performance Characteristics and Benchmarks"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In production tests, Nanonets OCR S ocr exhibits an average latency of 1.5 seconds for a 1024x768 image on the standard tier, with 99th percentile latency under 3 seconds. Accuracy metrics are strong: word error rate (WER) of 2.1% on printed text and 8.3% on handwritten samples, based on internal benchmarks using the ICDAR dataset. These numbers make it competitive for real-time applications where speed and precision are balanced."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Cost is usage-based, at $0.10 per page for the first 1,000 pages monthly, dropping to $0.05 per page thereafter. This is more predictable than per-character pricing models, but teams should factor in potential overage fees. For high-volume scenarios, consider batching requests to reduce HTTP overhead."
          }
        ]
